Smart Aquarium – Senior Design Project

Team: Leo Angelini, Braedon Hansen, Jack Sigler, Robert Hoze, Fiona Okida

Project Overview

This project aims to create a fully automated aquarium that gives fish a safe and monitored environment without constant human intervention. Using a Raspberry Pi and a variety of sensors and actuators, the system monitors water quality and keeps fish fed on a schedule or on demand. It also provides lighting control, fish identification using AWS Rekognition, live video streaming via AWS Kinesis Video Streams, and a mobile app interface.

The Smart Aquarium communicates with the cloud through Amazon Web Services (AWS), using IoT Core to relay sensor readings and control commands, Lambda functions to perform backend processing, and DynamoDB and S3 to store data and images. A React Native mobile application allows users to monitor conditions remotely, toggle the LED lighting, initiate manual feedings, upload photos for fish identification, and watch a livestream of their tank.

Sensors & Actuators

The aquarium uses multiple sensors to monitor the environment and actuators to control it:

  • Turbidity sensor for water clarity
  • pH sensor to monitor water acidity/alkalinity
  • Temperature sensor to keep fish comfortable
  • Camera for livestreaming and image recognition
  • SG90 servo motor controlling a fish feeder
  • LED light strip to simulate day/night cycles

System Logic

System behaviour is governed by a set of flow charts. The LED lighting follows a schedule while still allowing manual override, the feeder dispenses at fixed times or when commanded by the user, and the camera flow splits into image recognition and livestream paths.

Materials & Estimated Cost

  • Raspberry Pi Pico (or similar microcontroller) — approx. US $20
  • Camera module — cost varies
  • LED light strip — included with enclosure
  • 20 gallon fish tank, gravel and plants — approx. US $60
  • pH sensor and interface board
  • Turbidity (TDS) sensor
  • Servo‑driven fish feeder — approx. US $20
  • Air pump — approx. US $10
  • Fish — approx. US $9
  • AWS services (IoT, Lambda, Rekognition, S3, DynamoDB, Kinesis) — variable, estimated a few hundred dollars for development

Responsibilities & Collaboration

The project was a team effort in which every member contributed across hardware, software and cloud tasks. Braedon took the lead on sensor selection and integration as well as designing the feeder mechanism and enclosure. Jack focused on the communication layer and wrote the Python scripts running on the Raspberry Pi that interface with AWS IoT shadows and MQTT messaging. Leo implemented the backend computing logic using AWS services and created the custom Rekognition workflow. Robert developed and debugged the cloud integration, implementing the automated feeding schedule, livestream and MQTT configuration. Fiona designed and built the React Native mobile app and its user interface. Although each of these roles had a primary owner, most parts were worked on by multiple people and everyone participated in troubleshooting and integration.
